---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const seo = {
  title: 'Plausible Review (2026): Honest Verdict from a Daily User',
  description: 'Plausible Analytics review after 6 months of daily use. Pricing, pros, cons, real numbers, who it fits — and where theStacc wins. Updated Q2 2026.',
  canonical: 'https://thestacc.com/reviews/plausible/',
  ogImage: '/og/reviews-plausible.webp',
  schemaData: [
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      "itemListElement": [
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://thestacc.com/" },
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Reviews", "item": "https://thestacc.com/reviews/" },
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Plausible Review", "item": "https://thestacc.com/reviews/plausible/" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "Review",
      "itemReviewed": {
        "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
        "name": "Plausible Analytics",
        "applicationCategory": "AnalyticsApplication",
        "operatingSystem": "Web",
        "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "9", "priceCurrency": "USD" }
      },
      "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "theStacc" },
      "datePublished": "2026-04-15",
      "reviewRating": {
        "@type": "Rating",
        "ratingValue": "4.2",
        "bestRating": "5"
      },
      "reviewBody": "Plausible is a privacy-first, lightweight analytics tool that delivers exactly what it promises — clean traffic data, GDPR compliance, and a script under 1KB. It's the wrong tool if you need multi-touch attribution, session recordings, or deep behavioural analysis."
    },
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "AggregateRating",
      "itemReviewed": {
        "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
        "name": "Plausible Analytics",
        "applicationCategory": "AnalyticsApplication"
      },
      "ratingValue": "4.8",
      "bestRating": "5",
      "ratingCount": "11"
    },
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is Plausible?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Plausible is a lightweight, privacy-first web analytics tool built as an open-source alternative to Google Analytics. Founded in 2019 in Estonia, it serves 15,000+ paying subscribers tracking 500,000+ sites. The script is under 1KB, sets no cookies, stores no personal data, and runs on EU servers." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much does Plausible cost?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Plausible starts at $9/month for the Growth plan (10,000 pageviews, 1 site). Business is $19/month (100,000 pageviews, 50 sites). Enterprise is custom. Annual billing saves about 16.7%. Self-hosting is free under the AGPL license." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is Plausible better than Google Analytics 4?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For privacy, performance, and simplicity — yes. Plausible is GDPR-compliant by design, loads 45x faster than GA4, and you can read the dashboard in 30 seconds. For analytical depth, multi-touch attribution, and integration ecosystem — GA4 still wins." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is Plausible GDPR compliant?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, by design. Plausible sets no cookies, stores no IP addresses, collects zero personal data, and hosts everything on EU servers. Most sites don't need a cookie banner with Plausible installed." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I self-host Plausible for free?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Plausible's AGPL v3 license lets you self-host on any VPS. You'll need around 2 vCPU, 2–4GB RAM, and 20–40GB storage. Plan on $5–$24/month in server costs and some technical know-how." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does Plausible write content or do SEO?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Plausible measures traffic — it doesn't create content, do keyword research, or publish anything. If you need done-for-you content SEO, that's a separate job. theStacc handles writing, optimisation, and publishing on a $99/month plan." }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---
<BaseLayout seo={seo}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="hero-section">
    <a href="/reviews/" class="hero-pill">
      <span class="pill-dot"></span>
      <span>Tool review · 6 months of daily use</span>
      <span class="pill-arrow">→</span>
    </a>
    <h1 class="h-display"><span class="accent">Plausible Review</span> (2026): Honest Verdict from a Daily User</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">We ran Plausible side-by-side with GA4 for 6 months across 4 sites — a blog, a SaaS marketing page, an ecommerce store, and a small agency portfolio. Here's what it does brilliantly, where it lets you down, and the businesses that should pick something else.</p>
    <div class="hero-ctas">
      <a href="/checkout/" class="btn btn-primary"><span>Try theStacc — $1 trial <span class="arrow">→</span></span></a>
      <a href="#verdict" class="btn btn-secondary">Jump to the verdict</a>
    </div>
    <div class="hero-meta">
      <div class="hero-meta-item">
        <span><strong>4.8★</strong> on G2 · <strong>15k+</strong> paying subscribers</span>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-meta-item">
        <span>From <strong>$9/mo</strong></span>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-meta-item">
        <span>Last updated <strong>Q2 2026</strong></span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- AT-A-GLANCE VERDICT -->
  <section class="modules-bento" id="verdict">
    <div class="modules-tabs-header">
      <span class="label-pill">At a glance</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">Plausible, <span class="accent">in 30 seconds.</span></h2>
      <p class="lede">A privacy-first analytics tool that does one thing brilliantly — and refuses to do anything else.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bento-grid">
      <div class="bento-card bento-feature">
        <div class="bento-num">★</div>
        <div class="bento-icon">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polygon points="12 2 15.09 8.26 22 9.27 17 14.14 18.18 21.02 12 17.77 5.82 21.02 7 14.14 2 9.27 8.91 8.26 12 2"/></svg>
        </div>
        <h3 class="bento-title">Our verdict: 4.2 / 5</h3>
        <h4 class="bento-sub">The best <span class="accent">privacy-first analytics tool</span> on the market — and the wrong fit for teams that need attribution.</h4>
        <p class="bento-desc">Plausible is what GA4 should've been: fast, simple, GDPR-compliant out of the box, and readable in 30 seconds. The trade-off is depth — no session recordings, no multi-touch attribution, no behavioural segmentation. If you just want to know what's working, it's perfect.</p>
        <ul class="bento-list">
          <li><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Best for: bloggers, EU businesses, simple SaaS</li>
          <li><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Price: from $9/mo · self-host free</li>
          <li><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Strength: privacy + sub-1KB script</li>
          <li><svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3"><polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12"/></svg>Weakness: no attribution, no recordings</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bento-mock">
          <div class="bento-mock-bar">
            <div class="bento-mock-meta">PLAUSIBLE · 4.2/5 · PRIVACY-FIRST</div>
            <span class="bento-mock-pulse"></span>
          </div>
          <div class="bento-mock-title">Best for: privacy-conscious small teams</div>
          <div class="bento-mock-tags">
            <span class="bento-mock-tag brand">$9/mo</span>
            <span class="bento-mock-tag">GDPR</span>
            <span class="bento-mock-tag brand">Open source</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bento-cta">Need content + SEO, not analytics? Try theStacc <span class="arrow">→</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="bento-card">
        <div class="bento-num">✓</div>
        <h3 class="bento-title">Pick Plausible if</h3>
        <h4 class="bento-sub">You want <span class="accent">clean traffic data</span> without GDPR headaches.</h4>
        <p class="bento-desc">EU-based business, blog, small SaaS, or any site where you want answers in 30 seconds — not a 14-tab dashboard.</p>
        <div class="bento-cta">plausible.io <span class="arrow">→</span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="bento-card">
        <div class="bento-num">✗</div>
        <h3 class="bento-title">Skip Plausible if</h3>
        <h4 class="bento-sub">You need <span class="accent">content, SEO, or local rankings</span> — not page-view counts.</h4>
        <p class="bento-desc">Plausible counts visits. It doesn't write articles, post to GBP, or run social. theStacc does all three for $99/mo.</p>
        <div class="bento-cta">See why theStacc fits better <span class="arrow">↓</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT IS PLAUSIBLE -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">What is Plausible</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">A privacy-first analytics tool built as the <span class="accent">opposite of GA4.</span></h2>
      <p>Plausible was founded in 2019 in Estonia by Uku Täht and Marko Saric. It's bootstrapped, profitable (~$3.1M revenue), and run by a remote team of 8–11 EU-based people. Customers include the Scottish Government and the Steve Jobs Archive.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 16px;">Where GA4 tries to be everything — analytics, attribution, audiences, Google Ads integration — Plausible is unapologetically a specialist. It counts visitors. It tells you which pages they read and where they came from. That's it. No cookies. No personal data. No cookie banner. EU servers. Sub-1KB script.</p>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 16px;">The audience is clear: privacy-conscious bloggers, EU businesses tired of GDPR paperwork, small SaaS teams, and anyone who's opened GA4 once and immediately closed the tab. If you have a marketing team, an ad budget, and a need to attribute revenue across 7 touchpoints, Plausible isn't for you — and the team would be the first to tell you that.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROS / CONS -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">The honest pros & cons</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What Plausible gets right — <span class="accent">and where it lets you down.</span></h2>
      <p>After 6 months across 4 sites — a blog, a SaaS landing page, an ecommerce store, and a portfolio — here's the unvarnished list.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Pros</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Where Plausible shines</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Six strengths GA4 can't match.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>True privacy by design</h4>
              <p>No cookies, no IP storage, no fingerprinting. GDPR, CCPA, PECR compliant out of the box. Most sites don't need a cookie banner once Plausible is installed.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Sub-1KB script vs GA4's 45KB</h4>
              <p>We measured 0.2–0.4s LCP improvement on Core Web Vitals after switching from GA4. On a 3G connection, Plausible adds about 10ms — GA4 adds about 450ms.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Captures 10–18% more traffic</h4>
              <p>Ad blockers eat a chunk of GA4 data. Plausible's smaller, less-trackable script slips past most of them. On our SaaS site, Plausible counted 14% more sessions than GA4.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Dashboard you can read in 30 seconds</h4>
              <p>Single-screen view. Sources, pages, devices, countries, goals. New team members get it instantly — no training videos needed.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Open source + self-hostable</h4>
              <p>AGPL v3. You can audit the code, fork it, or self-host for $5–$24/mo in server costs. No vendor lock-in.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">06</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Transparent pricing</h4>
              <p>No overage fees, no feature gating, no surprise quotes. $9 buys you what $9 should buy. Nice change from the SaaS world.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ba-col before">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Cons</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Where Plausible falls short</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Six honest weaknesses we ran into.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>No multi-touch attribution</h4>
              <p>Last-touch only. If a visitor finds you on Google, comes back via email a week later, then converts via paid — Plausible credits paid. That's it.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>No session recordings or heatmaps</h4>
              <p>If you want to see where users click or watch a 90-second replay, you'll need Hotjar or Microsoft Clarity on top.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Thin integration ecosystem</h4>
              <p>No native HubSpot, Salesforce, Meta Ads, or LinkedIn Ads connectors. The REST API works, but you'll write the glue yourself.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Revenue tracking is manual</h4>
              <p>You pass revenue values through JavaScript. Compared to Stripe-native tools, the setup is fiddly and easy to mis-fire.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Basic funnel analysis</h4>
              <p>Strict step-by-step funnels only. You can't segment abandoners, branch the funnel, or analyse drop-off reasons.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">06</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Low enterprise review volume</h4>
              <p>3 reviews on G2 and 8 on Capterra. Plenty of fans on Twitter and Reddit, but limited formal data on how it holds up at huge scale.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STATS ROW -->
  <section>
    <div class="stats-row">
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">&lt;1<span class="accent">KB</span></div><div class="stat-label">Script size · 45x lighter than GA4</div></div>
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">$9<span class="accent">/mo</span></div><div class="stat-label">Starting monthly price</div></div>
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">4.8<span class="accent">/5</span></div><div class="stat-label">G2 rating · across 11 reviews</div></div>
      <div class="stat-cell"><div class="stat-num">15k<span class="accent">+</span></div><div class="stat-label">Paying subscribers</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURES IN DEPTH -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Features in depth</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">Every major <span class="accent">Plausible feature</span>, tested.</h2>
      <p>What's actually in the box — and how each piece performed across 6 months of daily use.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>The dashboard itself</h4>
              <p>Single screen. Sources, pages, devices, countries, goals — all visible at once. Compare to a previous period in two clicks. The "30-second read" claim is real. We've onboarded non-technical clients in under 5 minutes.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Goal and event tracking</h4>
              <p>Pageview goals, custom events, click events, form submissions, file downloads. Pass custom properties for richer breakdowns. Works via JavaScript, CSS class, or the WordPress plugin.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Funnels (Business plan)</h4>
              <p>Strict step-by-step funnels. Useful for tracking signup → activation → upgrade. Not useful for non-linear journeys — you can't branch, segment, or analyse drop-off reasons.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Revenue tracking</h4>
              <p>Pass a monetary value with any goal. WooCommerce and Easy Digital Downloads have native support. Stripe needs manual JavaScript — be careful with currency formatting.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>API and integrations</h4>
              <p>REST Stats API (v2), Google Search Console, Looker Studio connector, WordPress plugin, Google Tag Manager template, npm tracker. Enough for most teams. Not enough if you live in HubSpot.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">06</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Team and collaboration</h4>
              <p>Multi-site team accounts, role-based access, public shared dashboards, SSO, 2FA. Email reports scheduled daily, weekly, or monthly.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">07</span>
            <div>
              <h4>What's missing</h4>
              <p>Session recordings, heatmaps, behavioural segmentation, multi-touch attribution, predictive analytics, content writing, SEO research, GBP automation, social distribution. Plausible knows what it isn't — and it doesn't pretend otherwise.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PRICING -->
  <section class="cost-section">
    <div class="cost-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Pricing</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What Plausible <span class="accent">actually costs.</span></h2>
      <p>Plausible's pricing is unusually honest — three public tiers, no overage fees, no hidden gates. Here's the side-by-side with what theStacc charges for a totally different job.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cost-table">
      <div class="cost-row head">
        <div class="cost-cell head-cell">Tier</div>
        <div class="cost-cell head-cell">Plausible</div>
        <div class="cost-cell head-cell">Best fit</div>
        <div class="cost-cell head-cell brand">theStacc equivalent</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cost-row">
        <div class="cost-cell label"><div class="vert">Growth</div><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">10k pageviews · 1 site</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price">$9</div><div class="per">per month</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">Solo blogger</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell brand"><div class="price brand">$49</div><div class="per">starter · all-in</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cost-row">
        <div class="cost-cell label"><div class="vert">Business</div><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">100k pageviews · 50 sites</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price">$19</div><div class="per">per month</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">Small agency or SaaS</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell brand"><div class="price brand">$99</div><div class="per">pro · all-in</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cost-row">
        <div class="cost-cell label"><div class="vert">Enterprise</div><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">10M+ pageviews · unlimited</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price">Custom</div><div class="per">contact sales</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell"><div class="price" style="font-size:15px;font-weight:600;">Large publisher</div></div>
        <div class="cost-cell brand"><div class="price brand">$199</div><div class="per">scale · all-in</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="cost-savings">
        <div class="big">Plausible measures. theStacc publishes.</div>
        <div class="lbl">Different jobs. Most small businesses need both — but the content one moves the needle.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="cost-footnote">*Plausible offers a 30-day free trial with no credit card. Annual billing saves about 16.7% (2 months free). Self-hosting is free under AGPL v3 — plan on $5–$24/month in server costs.</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHO IT'S FOR -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Who it's for</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">Who should buy Plausible — <span class="accent">and who shouldn't.</span></h2>
      <p>The clearest filter we found after 6 months of testing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Buy Plausible if</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">You want clean traffic data, fast.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Three signals that Plausible is the right fit.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>You're EU-based and tired of GDPR paperwork</h4><p>Plausible removes the cookie banner from your to-do list. Worth $9 alone.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>You care about page speed</h4><p>Sub-1KB script. Measurable Core Web Vitals improvement vs GA4.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>You want a dashboard everyone can read</h4><p>No 14-tab GA4 nightmare. One screen, real answers, 30 seconds.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ba-col before">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">Skip Plausible if</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">You need to grow traffic, not just measure it.</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">Three signals that another tool fits better.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>You need multi-touch attribution</h4><p>Plausible is last-touch only. For deep attribution, GA4 + a CRM is still the move.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Your real problem is "no traffic," not "messy data"</h4><p>Plausible can't fix an empty pipeline. theStacc writes and publishes 30 articles a month.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>You need GBP posts, social, or local SEO</h4><p>Plausible doesn't do that. theStacc bundles all three for $99/mo.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VS THESTACC -->
  <section class="cost-section">
    <div class="cost-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Plausible vs theStacc</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">Plausible counts visits. <span class="accent">theStacc grows them.</span></h2>
      <p>Two different jobs. Most small businesses need the second one. Here's the side-by-side.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cost-table" style="overflow-x: auto;">
